\section{Subject Index}
The subject index follows after all contributions.

Care has to be taken that only words are included that are of help when
searching for a certain subject. Words from headings are unnecessary in the
index, as these are easily found through the table of contents. All words,
i.e., main entries as well as subentries, are listed in the basic form,
e.g., nouns in the singular, verbs in the infinitive. First-level entries
are capitalized.

You have either to mark the index entries with help of the
\verb|\index{<entry>}| command in the contributions or to collect them
manually. Sorting and formatting of the index can be done with the program
{\it MakeIndex}
or manually -- if MakeIndex is not implemented in your \LaTeX{} installation.
For details, we refer to \LaTeX{} manuals.

In case you generate the index with MakeIndex, start the program by typing
{\tt MAKEINDEX -S SPRMINDX.STY <filename>}.
{\tt SPRMINDX.STY} is a file included in our macro package containing
commands which modify the standard output of MakeIndex.

To print the index use the command \verb|\printindex|.
In case you generate the index manually
the input for the items of the subject index must be stored in a
separate dataset called \verb|<filename>.ind|. This file has the
following structure:

\begin{description}
\item[--] It starts with \verb|\begin{theindex}| and ends with
         \verb|\end{theindex}|.
\item[--] First level entries are coded as\\
         \verb|\item <entry>\idxquad <pagenumber(s)>|
\item[--] If there is more than one page number, separate them by
         \verb|,\,|
\item[--] A range of page numbers is entered in the form\\
         \verb|<firstpage>--<last page>|
\item[--] If reference to another entry instead of a page number is
         required, then type \verb|{\it see} <second entry>|
\item[--] Second and third-level entries have the forms
\item[ ] \verb|\subitem <entry>\idxquad <pagenumber(s)>| and
\item[ ] \verb|\subsubitem <entry>\idxquad <pagenumber(s)>|
respectively.
\item[--] Separate blocks of entries with different initial letters
using
         the command \verb|\indexspace|, which adds a little vertical
         space.
\end{description}

